Package com.github.tommyettinger.ds

Class LongDeque

java.lang.Object
com.github.tommyettinger.ds.LongDeque
All Implemented Interfaces:
Arrangeable, PrimitiveCollection<Long>, PrimitiveCollection.OfLong
public class LongDeque extends Object implements PrimitiveCollection.OfLong, Arrangeable
A resizable, insertion-ordered double-ended queue of longs with efficient add and remove at the beginning and end. Values in the backing array may wrap back to the beginning, making add and remove at the beginning and end O(1) (unless the backing array needs to resize when adding). Deque functionality is provided via removeLast() and addFirst(long).
Unlike most Deque implementations in the JDK, you can get and set items anywhere in the deque in constant time with get(int) and set(int, long).

    • values

      protected long[] values
      Contains the values in the queue. Head and tail indices go in a circle around this array, wrapping at the end.

    • head

      protected int head
      Index of first element. Logically smaller than tail. Unless empty, it points to a valid element inside queue.

    • tail

      protected int tail
      Index of last element. Logically bigger than head. Usually points to an empty position, but points to the head when full (size == values.length).

    • size

      Number of elements in the queue.

      public long[] toArray()
      Returns an array containing all of the elements in this collection. If this collection makes any guarantees as to what order its elements are returned by its iterator, this method must return the elements in the same order. The returned array's runtime component type is Object.

      The returned array will be "safe" in that no references to it are maintained by this collection. (In other words, this method must allocate a new array even if this collection is backed by an array). The caller is thus free to modify the returned array.

    • sort

      public void sort()
      Sorts this deque in-place using Arrays.sort(long[], int, int). This should operate in O(n log(n)) time or less when the internals of the deque are continuous (the head is before the tail in the array). If the internals are not continuous, this takes an additional O(n) step (where n is less than the size of the deque) to rearrange the internals before sorting.
